projects:
[{'title': 'Interpretation of the contact between Chozas Formation and Azagador Member (Turre Formation): implications on the tectono-stratigraphic evolution of the Sorbas basin (Spain).', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}}, 'description': 'Description of the topic: Collecting fault data, analyzing the relationship with the syn-kinematic sedimentation and completing detailed logs of 6 outcrops of the contact between the Chozas- Azagador Fm (turbidites-limestones), to describe the depositional environment and its temporal evolution.
', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Nikoleta', 'last_name': 'Santa', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Geotechnical Engineer ll at Fugro'}]}, {'title': 'Investigation of the mechanical behavior of the rock mass in Naypaktos area, Greece, for the construction of a tunnel, classification with RMR, GSI, and Q systems and horizontal alignment of the slope position.', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}}, 'description': 'Description of the topic: Collecting fault data and analyzing the factors that directly affect the mechanical behavior of the rock-mass, slope stability analysis was performed for the construction of a tunnel passing through limestone rocks. Additionally, rock-mass classification with RMR, GSI, and Q systems took place to estimate the quality of rock-mass. Using Autocad, the horizontal alignment of the outcrop position was described. Finally, the future position of the tunnel was analyzed by taking into consideration the orientation of the fault systems, and the low quality of the fractured rock-mass.
', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Nikoleta', 'last_name': 'Santa', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Geotechnical Engineer ll at Fugro'}]}, {'title': 'MSc title: Subaqueous and Subaerial Debris-flow deposits: physical experiments of debris-flows lake interactions, and controls on subaqueous flow deposits.', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}, 'end': {'month': 4, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}}, 'description': 'Description of the topic: I performed a small-scale subaqueous and subaerial debris-flow experiments to analyze and compare the deposit dimensions.  Specifically, I developed a multi-phase subaqueous and subaerial debris-flow, and I focused on the effect of mass (3.5-18.0 kg), composition (e.g., water 40-60%, gravel 0-64%, and clay 0-29%), and outflow channel slope (20-400) on subaqueous and subaerial debris flow deposit dimensions and grain size sorting. The experimental setup consists of a 2.0 m outflow channel slope with a varied angle such as 20-400, a 0.90 m wide and 1.85 m long basin, and a 100 inclined outflow plain bed. The basin is either filled with water for the subaqueous runs with a water depth of 0.33 m, or empty for the subaerial runs. Debris flow deposit dimensions are highly dependent on flow momentum and velocity. Therefore, debris flow deposit runout distance, width, and thickness are controlled by the flow mass, composition, and slope variations.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Nikoleta', 'last_name': 'Santa', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Geotechnical Engineer ll at Fugro'}]}, {'title': 'MSc title: Rockfalls due to the Recent Earthquakes in Lefkas island: Inventory, Technicogeological Conditions of rock mass, Numerical Simulations.', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}, 'end': {'month': 8, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}}, 'description': "Description of the topic: Initially, landslides monitoring and investigation, and the geological mapping of the island's various formations took place in order to analyze the new elements and compare them with maps that existed from previous studies so as to reach the 5 technico-geological units which separates the island.
 In situ and laboratory tests of the rock-mass were necessary to classify individual the physical and mechanical characteristics of the rock-mass, and to create a technical-geological map of the island at a scale of 1: 5000 using Arc GIS. In a final stage, collecting data from 4 stations in different areas including accelerometers, the components of the Peak Ground Acceleration were measured to characterize the ground acceleration. 
", 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Nikoleta', 'last_name': 'Santa', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Geotechnical Engineer ll at Fugro'}]}, {'title': 'BSc title: Simulation of Rockfalls with Computational Methods in Static and Dynamic Load Conditions, Application in the Area of Eggremnoi and Porto Katsiki, in Lefkas Island, Greece.', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2014}, 'end': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}}, 'description': None, 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Nikoleta', 'last_name': 'Santa', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Geotechnical Engineer ll at Fugro'}]}]
